# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mpi-parallel-computing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] In computer science, **distributed memory** refers to a multiprocessor computer system in which each processor has its own private memory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] Computational tasks can only operate on local data, and if remote data are required, the computational task must communicate with one or more remote processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] In contrast, a shared memory multiprocessor offers a single memory space used by all processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] Processors do not have to be aware where data resides, except that there may be performance penalties, and that race conditions are to be avoided.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] In a distributed memory system there is typically a processor, a memory, and some form of interconnection that allows programs on each processor to interact with each other.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] The interconnect can be organised with point to point links or separate hardware can provide a switching network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] The network topology is a key factor in determining how the multiprocessor machine scales.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] The links between nodes can be implemented using some standard network protocol (for example Ethernet), using bespoke network links (used in for example the transputer), or using dual-ported memories.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] The key issue in programming distributed memory systems is how to distribute the data over the memories.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] Depending on the problem solved, the data can be distributed statically, or it can be moved through the nodes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] Data can be moved on demand, or data can be pushed to the new nodes in advance.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] As an example, if a problem can be described as a pipeline where data *x* is processed subsequently through functions *f*, *g*, *h*, etc.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] (the result is *h*(*g*(*f*(*x*)))), then this can be expressed as a distributed memory problem where the data is transmitted first to the node that performs *f* that passes the result onto the second node that computes *g*, and finally to the third node that computes *h*.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] This is also known as systolic computation.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] Data can be kept statically in nodes if most computations happen locally, and only changes on edges have to be reported to other nodes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] An example of this is simulation where data is modeled using a grid, and each node simulates a small part of the larger grid.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] On every iteration, nodes inform all neighboring nodes of the new edge data.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] Similarly, in distributed shared memory each node of a cluster has access to a large shared memory in addition to each node's limited non-shared private memory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/distributed-memory] Distributed shared memory hides the mechanism of communication, it does not hide the latency of communication.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The **Message Passing Interface** (**MPI**) is a portable message-passing standard designed to function on parallel computing architectures.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The MPI standard defines the syntax and semantics of library routines that are useful to a wide range of users writing portable message-passing programs in C, C++, and Fortran.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] There are several open-source MPI implementations, which fostered the development of a parallel software industry, and encouraged development of portable and scalable large-scale parallel applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The message passing interface effort began in the summer of 1991 when a small group of researchers started discussions at a mountain retreat in Austria.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Out of that discussion came a Workshop on Standards for Message Passing in a Distributed Memory Environment, held on April 29–30, 1992 in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Attendees at Williamsburg discussed the basic features essential to a standard message-passing interface and established a working group to continue the standardization process.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Walker put forward a preliminary draft proposal, "MPI1", in November 1992.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In November 1992 a meeting of the MPI working group took place in Minneapolis and decided to place the standardization process on a more formal footing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The MPI working group met every 6 weeks throughout the first 9 months of 1993.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The draft MPI standard was presented at the Supercomputing '93 conference in November 1993.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] After a period of public comments, which resulted in some changes in MPI, version 1.0 of MPI was released in June 1994.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] These meetings and the email discussion together constituted the MPI Forum, membership of which has been open to all members of the high-performance-computing community.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The MPI effort involved about 80 people from 40 organizations, mainly in the United States and Europe.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Most of the major vendors of concurrent computers were involved in the MPI effort, collaborating with researchers from universities, government laboratories, and industry.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI provides parallel hardware vendors with a clearly defined base set of routines that can be efficiently implemented.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] As a result, hardware vendors can build upon this collection of standard low-level routines to create higher-level routines for the distributed-memory communication environment supplied with their parallel machines.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI provides a simple-to-use portable interface for the basic user, yet one powerful enough to allow programmers to use the high-performance message passing operations available on advanced machines.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In an effort to create a universal standard for message passing, researchers did not base it off of a single system but it incorporated the most useful features of several systems, including those designed by IBM, Intel, nCUBE, PVM, Express, P4 and PARMACS.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The message-passing paradigm is attractive because of wide portability and can be used in communication for distributed-memory and shared-memory multiprocessors, networks of workstations, and a combination of these elements.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The paradigm can apply in multiple settings, independent of network speed or memory architecture.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Support for MPI meetings came in part from DARPA and from the U.S.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] National Science Foundation (NSF) under grant ASC-9310330, NSF Science and Technology Center Cooperative agreement number CCR-8809615, and from the European Commission through Esprit Project P6643.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The University of Tennessee also made financial contributions to the MPI Forum.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In subsequent years the MPI standard has evolved through multiple major and minor revisions, each introducing new capabilities and improvements.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI is a communication protocol for programming parallel computers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Both point-to-point and collective communication are supported.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI "is a message-passing application programmer interface, together with protocol and semantic specifications for how its features must behave in any implementation".
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI's goals are high performance, scalability, and portability.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI remained the dominant model used in high-performance computing as of 2006.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The standard’s goals include high performance, scalability, and portability across parallel computing architectures.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Although not governed by a formal international standards body, MPI is widely regarded as a de facto standard for message passing in high-performance computing applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI is not sanctioned by any major standards body; nevertheless, it has become a de facto standard for communication among processes that model a parallel program running on a distributed memory system.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Actual distributed memory supercomputers such as computer clusters often run such programs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The principal MPI-1 model has no shared memory concept, and MPI-2 has only a limited distributed shared memory concept.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Nonetheless, MPI programs are regularly run on shared-memory computers, and both MPICH and Open MPI can use shared memory for message transfer if it is available.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Designing programs around the MPI model (contrary to explicit shared memory models) has advantages when running on NUMA architectures, since MPI encourages memory locality.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Explicit shared-memory programming was introduced in MPI-3.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Although MPI belongs in layers 5 and higher of the OSI Reference Model, implementations may cover most layers, with sockets and Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) used in the transport layer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Most MPI implementations consist of a specific set of routines directly callable from C, C++, Fortran (i.e., an API) and any language able to interface with such libraries, including C#, Java or Python.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The advantages of MPI over older message-passing libraries are portability (because MPI has been implemented for almost every distributed-memory architecture) and speed (because each implementation is in principle optimized for the hardware on which it runs).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI uses Language Independent Specifications (LIS) for calls and language bindings.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The first MPI standard specified ANSI C and Fortran 77 bindings together with the LIS.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The draft was presented at Supercomputing 1994 (November 1994) and finalized soon thereafter.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] About 128 functions constitute the MPI-1.3 standard, which was released as the final end of the MPI-1 series in 2008.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI-2's LIS specifies over 500 functions and provides language bindings for ISO C, ISO C++, and Fortran 90.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Object interoperability was also added to allow easier mixed-language message-passing programming.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] A side-effect of standardizing MPI-2, completed in 1996, was clarifying the MPI-1 standard, creating the MPI-1.2.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI is often compared with Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM), which was a popular distributed environment and message-passing system developed in 1989, and which was one of the systems that motivated the need for standard parallel message passing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Threaded shared-memory programming models (such as Pthreads and OpenMP) and message-passing programming (MPI/PVM) can be considered complementary and have been used together on occasion in, for example, servers with multiple large shared-memory nodes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI programs always work with processes, but programmers commonly refer to the processes as processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Typically, for maximum performance, each CPU (or core in a multi-core machine) will be assigned just a single process.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] This assignment happens at runtime through the agent that starts the MPI program, normally called mpirun or mpiexec.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI supports both **point-to-point communication**, where messages are exchanged directly between pairs of processes, and **collective communication**, where groups of processes cooperate on operations such as broadcast and reduction.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Language bindings allow MPI routines to be used from multiple programming languages, with the C and Fortran bindings being the most common.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Point-to-point operations come in synchronous, asynchronous, buffered, and *ready* forms, to allow both relatively stronger and weaker semantics for the synchronization aspects of a rendezvous-send.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Many pending operations are possible in asynchronous mode, in most implementations.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI-1 and MPI-2 both enable implementations that overlap communication and computation, but practice and theory differ.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI also specifies *thread safe* interfaces, which have cohesion and coupling strategies that help avoid hidden state within the interface.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] It is relatively easy to write multithreaded point-to-point MPI code, and some implementations support such code.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Multithreaded collective communication is best accomplished with multiple copies of Communicators, as described below.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The following concepts provide context for all of those abilities and help the programmer to decide what functionality to use in their application programs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Four of MPI's eight basic concepts are unique to MPI-2.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Communicator objects connect groups of processes in the MPI session.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Each communicator gives each contained process an independent identifier and arranges its contained processes in an ordered topology.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI also has explicit groups, but these are mainly good for organizing and reorganizing groups of processes before another communicator is made.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI understands single group intracommunicator operations, and bilateral intercommunicator communication.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In MPI-1, single group operations are most prevalent.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Bilateral operations mostly appear in MPI-2 where they include collective communication and dynamic in-process management.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Communicators can be partitioned using several MPI commands.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] These commands include `MPI_COMM_SPLIT`, where each process joins one of several colored sub-communicators by declaring itself to have that color.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] A number of important MPI functions involve communication between two specific processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] A popular example is `MPI_Send`, which allows one specified process to send a message to a second specified process.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI-1 specifies mechanisms for both blocking and non-blocking point-to-point communication mechanisms, as well as the so-called 'ready-send' mechanism whereby a send request can be made only when the matching receive request has already been made.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Collective functions involve communication among all processes in a process group (which can mean the entire process pool or a program-defined subset).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] A typical function is the `MPI_Bcast` call (short for "broadcast").
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] This function takes data from one node and sends it to all processes in the process group.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] A reverse operation is the `MPI_Reduce` call, which takes data from all processes in a group, performs an operation (such as summing), and stores the results on one node.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] `MPI_Reduce` is often useful at the start or end of a large distributed calculation, where each processor operates on a part of the data and then combines it into a result.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Other operations perform more sophisticated tasks, such as `MPI_Alltoall` which rearranges *n* items of data such that the *n*th node gets the *n*th item of data from each.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Many MPI functions require specifing the type of data which is sent between processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] This is because MPI aims to support heterogeneous environments where types might be represented differently on the different nodes (for example they might be running different CPU architectures that have different endianness), in which case MPI implementations can perform *data conversion*.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Since the C language does not allow a type itself to be passed as a parameter, MPI predefines the constants `MPI_INT`, `MPI_CHAR`, `MPI_DOUBLE` to correspond with `int`, `char`, `double`, etc.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Here is an example in C that passes arrays of `int`s from all processes to one.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The one receiving process is called the "root" process, and it can be any designated process but normally it will be process 0.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] However, it may be instead desirable to send data as one block as opposed to 100 `int`s.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The `disp` (displacements) array is needed for data structure alignment, since the compiler may pad the variables in a class or data structure.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The safest way to find the distance between different fields is by obtaining their addresses in memory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] This is done with `MPI_Get_address`, which is normally the same as C's `&` operator but that might not be true when dealing with memory segmentation.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Passing a data structure as one block is significantly faster than passing one item at a time, especially if the operation is to be repeated.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] This is because fixed-size blocks do not require serialization during transfer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI-2 defines three one-sided communications operations, `MPI_Put`, `MPI_Get`, and `MPI_Accumulate`, being a write to remote memory, a read from remote memory, and a reduction operation on the same memory across a number of tasks, respectively.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Also defined are three different methods to synchronize this communication (global, pairwise, and remote locks) as the specification does not guarantee that these operations have taken place until a synchronization point.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] These types of call can often be useful for algorithms in which synchronization would be inconvenient (e.g. distributed matrix multiplication), or where it is desirable for tasks to be able to balance their load while other processors are operating on data.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The `MPI_Comm_spawn` interface allows an MPI process to spawn a number of instances of the named MPI process.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The newly spawned set of MPI processes form a new `MPI_COMM_WORLD` intracommunicator but can communicate with the parent and the intercommunicator the function returns.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] `MPI_Comm_spawn_multiple` is an alternate interface that allows the different instances spawned to be different binaries with different arguments.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The parallel I/O feature is sometimes called MPI-IO, and refers to a set of functions designed to abstract I/O management on distributed systems to MPI, and allow files to be easily accessed in a patterned way using the existing derived datatype functionality.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The little research that has been done on this feature indicates that it may not be trivial to get high performance gains by using MPI-IO.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] For example, an implementation of sparse matrix-vector multiplications using the MPI I/O library shows a general behavior of minor performance gain, but these results are inconclusive.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] It was not until the idea of collective I/O implemented into MPI-IO that MPI-IO started to reach widespread adoption.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Collective I/O substantially boosts applications' I/O bandwidth by having processes collectively transform the small and noncontiguous I/O operations into large and contiguous ones, thereby reducing the locking and disk seek overhead.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Due to its vast performance benefits, MPI-IO also became the underlying I/O layer for many state-of-the-art I/O libraries, such as HDF5 and Parallel NetCDF.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Its popularity also triggered research on collective I/O optimizations, such as layout-aware I/O and cross-file aggregation.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Many other efforts are derivatives of MPICH, LAM, and other works, including, but not limited to, commercial implementations from HPE, Intel, Microsoft, and NEC.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] While the specifications mandate a C and Fortran interface, the language used to implement MPI is not constrained to match the language or languages it seeks to support at runtime.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Most implementations combine C, C++ and assembly language, and target C, C++, and Fortran programmers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Bindings are available for many other languages, including Perl, Python, R, Ruby, Java, and CL (see #Language bindings).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The ABI of MPI implementations are roughly split between MPICH and Open MPI derivatives, so that a library from one family works as a drop-in replacement of one from the same family, but direct replacement across families is impossible.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The French CEA maintains a wrapper interface to facilitate such switches.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI hardware research focuses on implementing MPI directly in hardware, for example via processor-in-memory, building MPI operations into the microcircuitry of the RAM chips in each node.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] By implication, this approach is independent of language, operating system, and CPU, but cannot be readily updated or removed.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Another approach has been to add hardware acceleration to one or more parts of the operation, including hardware processing of MPI queues and using RDMA to directly transfer data between memory and the network interface controller without CPU or OS kernel intervention.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Bindings are libraries that extend MPI support to other languages by wrapping an existing MPI implementation such as MPICH or Open MPI.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The two managed Common Language Infrastructure .NET implementations are Pure Mpi.NET and MPI.NET, a research effort at Indiana University licensed under a BSD-style license.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] It is compatible with Mono, and can make full use of underlying low-latency MPI network fabrics.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Although Java does not have an official MPI binding, several groups attempt to bridge the two, with different degrees of success and compatibility.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] One of the first attempts was Bryan Carpenter's mpiJava, essentially a set of Java Native Interface (JNI) wrappers to a local C MPI library, resulting in a hybrid implementation with limited portability, which also has to be compiled against the specific MPI library being used.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] However, this original project also defined the mpiJava API (a de facto MPI API for Java that closely followed the equivalent C++ bindings) which other subsequent Java MPI projects adopted.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] One less-used API is MPJ API, which was designed to be more object-oriented and closer to Sun Microsystems' coding conventions.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Beyond the API, Java MPI libraries can be either dependent on a local MPI library, or implement the message passing functions in Java, while some like P2P-MPI also provide peer-to-peer functionality and allow mixed-platform operation.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Some of the most challenging parts of Java/MPI arise from Java characteristics such as the lack of explicit pointers and the linear memory address space for its objects, which make transferring multidimensional arrays and complex objects inefficient.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Another Java message passing system is MPJ Express.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Recent versions can be executed in cluster and multicore configurations.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In the cluster configuration, it can execute parallel Java applications on clusters and clouds.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Here Java sockets or specialized I/O interconnects like Myrinet can support messaging between MPJ Express processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] It can also utilize native C implementation of MPI using its native device.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In the multicore configuration, a parallel Java application is executed on multicore processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In this mode, MPJ Express processes are represented by Java threads.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] There is a Julia language wrapper for MPI.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] There are a few academic implementations of MPI using MATLAB.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MATLAB has its own parallel extension library implemented using MPI and PVM.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The OCamlMPI Module implements a large subset of MPI functions and is in active use in scientific computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] An 11,000-line OCaml program was "MPI-ified" using the module, with an additional 500 lines of code and slight restructuring and ran with excellent results on up to 170 nodes in a supercomputer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] PARI/GP can be built to use MPI as its multi-thread engine, allowing to run parallel PARI and GP programs on MPI clusters unmodified.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Actively maintained MPI wrappers for Python include: mpi4py, numba-mpi and numba-jax.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Discontinued developments include: pyMPI, pypar, MYMPI and the MPI submodule in ScientificPython.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] R bindings of MPI include Rmpi and pbdMPI, where Rmpi focuses on manager-workers parallelism while pbdMPI focuses on SPMD parallelism.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Both implementations fully support Open MPI or MPICH2.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Here is a "Hello, World!" program in MPI written in C.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In this example, we send a "hello" message to each processor, manipulate it trivially, return the results to the main process, and print the messages.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Here, `mpiexec` is a command used to execute the example program with 4 processes, each of which is an independent instance of the program at run time and assigned ranks (i.e. numeric IDs) 0, 1, 2, and 3.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The name `mpiexec` is recommended by the MPI standard, although some implementations provide a similar command under the name `mpirun`.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The `MPI_COMM_WORLD` is the communicator that consists of all the processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] A single program, multiple data (SPMD) programming model is thereby facilitated, but not required; many MPI implementations allow multiple, different, executables to be started in the same MPI job.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Each process has its own rank, the total number of processes in the world, and the ability to communicate between them either with point-to-point (send/receive) communication, or by collective communication among the group.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] It is enough for MPI to provide an SPMD-style program with `MPI_COMM_WORLD`, its own rank, and the size of the world to allow algorithms to decide what to do.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In more realistic situations, I/O is more carefully managed than in this example.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI does not stipulate how standard I/O (stdin, stdout, stderr) should work on a given system.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] It generally works as expected on the rank-0 process, and some implementations also capture and funnel the output from other processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI uses the notion of process rather than processor.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Program copies are *mapped* to processors by the MPI runtime.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] In that sense, the parallel machine can map to one physical processor, or to *N* processors, where *N* is the number of available processors, or even something in between.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] For maximum parallel speedup, more physical processors are used.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] This example adjusts its behavior to the size of the world *N*, so it also seeks to scale to the runtime configuration without compilation for each size variation, although runtime decisions might vary depending on that absolute amount of concurrency available.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Adoption of MPI-1.2 has been universal, particularly in cluster computing, but acceptance of MPI-2.1 has been more limited.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Many MPI-1.2 programs were developed before MPI-2.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Portability concerns initially slowed adoption, although wider support has lessened this.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Many MPI-1.2 applications use only a subset of that standard (16–25 functions) with no real need for MPI-2 functionality.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Some aspects of the MPI's future appear solid; others less so.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The MPI Forum reconvened in 2007 to clarify some MPI-2 issues and explore developments for a possible MPI-3, which resulted in versions MPI-3.0 (September 2012) and MPI-3.1 (June 2015).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] The development continued with the approval of MPI-4.0 on June 9, 2021,.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI-4.1 was approved on November 2, 2023., with MPI-5.0 being approved on June 5, 2025, bringing significant new functionality; notably the addition of a standard Application Binary Interface (ABI)..
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Architectures are changing, with greater internal concurrency (multi-core), better fine-grained concurrency control (threading, affinity), and more levels of memory hierarchy.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Multithreaded programs can take advantage of these developments more easily than single-threaded applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] This has already yielded separate, complementary standards for symmetric multiprocessing, namely OpenMP.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI-2 defines how standard-conforming implementations should deal with multithreaded issues, but does not require that implementations be multithreaded, or even thread-safe.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] MPI-3 adds the ability to use shared-memory parallelism within a node.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Implementations of MPI such as Adaptive MPI, Hybrid MPI, Fine-Grained MPI, MPC and others offer extensions to the MPI standard that address different challenges in MPI.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] Astrophysicist Jonathan Dursi wrote an opinion piece calling MPI obsolescent, pointing to newer technologies like the Chapel language, Unified Parallel C, Hadoop, Spark and Flink.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/message-passing-interface] At the same time, nearly all of the projects in the Exascale Computing Project build explicitly on MPI; MPI has been shown to scale to the largest machines as of the early 2020s and is widely considered to stay relevant for a long time to come.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] A **supercomputer** is a type of computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] They have been essential in the field of cryptanalysis.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The performance of a supercomputer is commonly measured in floating-point operations per second (FLOPS) instead of million instructions per second (MIPS).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Since 2022, exascale supercomputers have existed which can perform over 1018 FLOPS.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] For comparison, a desktop computer has performance in the range of hundreds of gigaFLOPS (1011) to tens of teraFLOPS (1013).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Since November 2017, all of the world's fastest 500 supercomputers run on Linux-based operating systems.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Additional research is being conducted in the United States, the European Union, Taiwan, Japan, and China to build faster, more powerful and technologically superior exascale supercomputers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Supercomputers were introduced in the 1960s, and for several decades the fastest was made by Seymour Cray at Control Data Corporation (CDC), Cray Research and subsequent companies bearing his name or monogram.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The first such machines were highly tuned conventional designs that ran quicker than their more general-purpose contemporaries.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Through the decade, increasing amounts of parallelism were added, with one to four processors being typical.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the 1970s, vector processors operating on large arrays of data came to dominate.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] A notable example is the highly successful Cray-1 of 1976.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Vector computers remained the dominant design into the 1990s.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] From then until today, massively parallel supercomputers with tens of thousands of off-the-shelf processors became the norm.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The U.S. has long been a leader in the supercomputer field, initially through Cray's nearly uninterrupted dominance, and later through a variety of technology companies.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Japan made significant advancements in the field during the 1980s and 1990s, while China has become increasingly active in supercomputing in recent years.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] As of November 2024, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory's El Capitan is the world's fastest supercomputer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The US has five of the top 10; Italy two, Japan, Finland, Switzerland have one each.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In 1960, UNIVAC built the Livermore Atomic Research Computer (LARC), today considered among the first supercomputers, for the US Navy Research and Development Center.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] It still used high-speed drum memory, rather than the newly emerging disk drive technology.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Also, among the first supercomputers was the IBM 7030 Stretch.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 was built by IBM for the Los Alamos National Laboratory, which then in 1955 had requested a computer 100 times faster than any existing computer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 used transistors, magnetic core memory, pipelined instructions, prefetched data through a memory controller and included pioneering random access disk drives.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 was completed in 1961 and despite not meeting the challenge of a hundredfold increase in performance, it was purchased by the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Customers in England and France also bought the computer, and it became the basis for the IBM 7950 Harvest, a supercomputer built for cryptanalysis.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The third pioneering supercomputer project in the early 1960s was the Atlas at the University of Manchester, built by a team led by Tom Kilburn.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] He designed the Atlas to have memory space for up to a million words of 48 bits, but because magnetic storage with such a capacity was unaffordable, the actual core memory of the Atlas was only 16,000 words, with a drum providing memory for a further 96,000 words.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Atlas Supervisor swapped data in the form of pages between the magnetic core and the drum.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Atlas operating system also introduced time-sharing to supercomputing, so that more than one program could be executed on the supercomputer at any one time.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Atlas was a joint venture between Ferranti and Manchester University and was designed to operate at processing speeds approaching one microsecond per instruction, about one million instructions per second.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The CDC 6600, designed by Seymour Cray, was finished in 1964 and marked the transition from germanium to silicon transistors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Silicon transistors could run more quickly and the overheating problem was solved by introducing refrigeration to the supercomputer design.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Thus, the CDC6600 became the fastest computer in the world.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Given that the 6600 outperformed all the other contemporary computers by about 10 times, it was dubbed a *supercomputer* and defined the supercomputing market, when one hundred computers were sold at $8 million each.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Cray left CDC in 1972 to form his own company, Cray Research.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Four years after leaving CDC, Cray delivered the 80 MHz Cray-1 in 1976, which became one of the most successful supercomputers in history.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] It had eight central processing units (CPUs), liquid cooling and the electronics coolant liquid Fluorinert was pumped through the supercomputer architecture.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] It reached 1.9 gigaFLOPS, making it the first supercomputer to break the gigaflop barrier.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The only computer to seriously challenge the Cray-1's performance in the 1970s was the ILLIAC IV.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] This machine was the first realized example of a true massively parallel computer, in which many processors worked together to solve different parts of a single larger problem.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In contrast with the vector systems, which were designed to run a single stream of data as quickly as possible, in this concept, the computer instead feeds separate parts of the data to entirely different processors and then recombines the results.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The ILLIAC's design was finalized in 1966 with 256 processors and offer speed up to 1 GFLOPS, compared to the 1970s Cray-1's peak of 250 MFLOPS.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] However, development problems led to only 64 processors being built, and the system could never operate more quickly than about 200 MFLOPS while being much larger and more complex than the Cray.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Another problem was that writing software for the system was difficult, and getting peak performance from it was a matter of serious effort.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] But the partial success of the ILLIAC IV was widely seen as pointing the way to the future of supercomputing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Cray argued against this, famously quipping that "If you were plowing a field, which would you rather use?
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Two strong oxen or 1024 chickens?" But by the early 1980s, several teams were working on parallel designs with thousands of processors, notably the Connection Machine (CM) that developed from research at MIT.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The CM-1 used as many as 65,536 simplified custom microprocessors connected together in a network to share data.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Several updated versions followed; the CM-5 supercomputer is a massively parallel processing computer capable of many billions of arithmetic operations per second.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In 1982, Osaka University's LINKS-1 Computer Graphics System used a massively parallel processing architecture, with 514 microprocessors, including 257 Zilog Z8001 control processors and 257 iAPX 86/20 floating-point processors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] It was mainly used for rendering realistic 3D computer graphics.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Fujitsu's VPP500 from 1992 is unusual since, to achieve higher speeds, its processors used GaAs, a material normally reserved for microwave applications due to its toxicity.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Fujitsu's Numerical Wind Tunnel supercomputer used 166 vector processors to gain the top spot in 1994 with a peak speed of 1.7 gigaFLOPS (GFLOPS) per processor.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Hitachi SR2201 obtained a peak performance of 600 GFLOPS in 1996 by using 2048 processors connected via a fast three-dimensional crossbar network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Intel Paragon could have 1000 to 4000 Intel i860 processors in various configurations and was ranked the fastest in the world in 1993.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Paragon was a MIMD machine which connected processors via a high speed two-dimensional mesh, allowing processes to execute on separate nodes, communicating via the Message Passing Interface.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Software development remained a problem, but the CM series sparked off considerable research into this issue.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Similar designs using custom hardware were made by many companies, including the Evans & Sutherland ES-1, MasPar, nCUBE, Intel iPSC and the Goodyear MPP.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] But by the mid-1990s, general-purpose CPU performance had improved so much in that a supercomputer could be built using them as the individual processing units, instead of using custom chips.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] By the turn of the 21st century, designs featuring tens of thousands of commodity CPUs were the norm, with later machines adding graphic units to the mix.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In 1998, David Bader developed the first Linux supercomputer using commodity parts.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] While at the University of New Mexico, Bader sought to build a supercomputer running Linux using consumer off-the-shelf parts and a high-speed low-latency interconnection network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The prototype utilized an Alta Technologies "AltaCluster" of eight dual, 333 MHz, Intel Pentium II computers running a modified Linux kernel.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Bader ported a significant amount of software to provide Linux support for necessary components as well as code from members of the National Computational Science Alliance (NCSA) to ensure interoperability, as none of it had been run on Linux previously.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Using the successful prototype design, he led the development of "RoadRunner," the first Linux supercomputer for open use by the national science and engineering community via the National Science Foundation's National Technology Grid.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] RoadRunner was put into production use in April 1999.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] At the time of its deployment, it was considered one of the 100 fastest supercomputers in the world.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Though Linux-based clusters using consumer-grade parts, such as Beowulf, existed prior to the development of Bader's prototype and RoadRunner, they lacked the scalability, bandwidth, and parallel computing capabilities to be considered "true" supercomputers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Systems with a massive number of processors generally take one of two paths.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the grid computing approach, the processing power of many computers, organized as distributed, diverse administrative domains, is opportunistically used whenever a computer is available.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In another approach, many processors are used in proximity to each other, e.g. in a computer cluster.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In such a centralized massively parallel system the speed and flexibility of the *interconnect* becomes very important and modern supercomputers have used various approaches ranging from enhanced Infiniband systems to three-dimensional torus interconnects.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The use of multi-core processors combined with centralization is an emerging direction, e.g. as in the Cyclops64 system.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] As the price, performance and energy efficiency of general-purpose graphics processing units (GPGPUs) have improved, a number of petaFLOPS supercomputers such as Tianhe-I and Nebulae have started to rely on them.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] However, GPUs are gaining ground, and in 2012 the Jaguar supercomputer was transformed into Titan by retrofitting CPUs with GPUs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] High-performance computers have an expected life cycle of about three years before requiring an upgrade.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Gyoukou supercomputer is unique in that it uses both a massively parallel design and liquid immersion cooling.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] A number of special-purpose systems have been designed, dedicated to a single problem.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] This allows the use of specially programmed FPGA chips or even custom ASICs, allowing better price/performance ratios by sacrificing generality.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Examples of special-purpose supercomputers include Belle, Deep Blue, and Hydra for playing chess, Gravity Pipe for astrophysics, MDGRAPE-3 for protein structure prediction and molecular dynamics, and Deep Crack for breaking the DES cipher.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Throughout the decades, the management of heat density has remained a key issue for most centralized supercomputers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The large amount of heat generated by a system may also have other effects, e.g. reducing the lifetime of other system components.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] There have been diverse approaches to heat management, from pumping Fluorinert through the system, to a hybrid liquid-air cooling system or air cooling with normal air conditioning temperatures.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] A typical supercomputer consumes large amounts of electrical power, almost all of which is converted into heat, requiring cooling.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] For example, Tianhe-1A consumes 4.04 megawatts (MW) of electricity.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The cost to power and cool the system can be significant, e.g.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] 4 MW at $0.10/kWh is $400 an hour or about $3.5 million per year.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Heat management is a major issue in complex electronic devices and affects powerful computer systems in various ways.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The thermal design power and CPU power dissipation issues in supercomputing surpass those of traditional computer cooling technologies.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The supercomputing awards for green computing reflect this issue.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The packing of thousands of processors together inevitably generates significant amounts of heat density that need to be dealt with.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Cray-2 was liquid cooled, and used a Fluorinert "cooling waterfall" which was forced through the modules under pressure.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] However, the submerged liquid cooling approach was not practical for the multi-cabinet systems based on off-the-shelf processors, and in System X a special cooling system that combined air conditioning with liquid cooling was developed in conjunction with the Liebert company.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the Blue Gene system, IBM deliberately used low power processors to deal with heat density.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The IBM Power 775, released in 2011, has closely packed elements that require water cooling.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The IBM Aquasar system uses hot water cooling to achieve energy efficiency, the water being used to heat buildings as well.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The energy efficiency of computer systems is generally measured in terms of "FLOPS per watt".
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In 2008, Roadrunner by IBM operated at 376 MFLOPS/W.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In November 2010, the Blue Gene/Q reached 1684 MFLOPS/W and in June 2011 the top two spots on the Green 500 list were occupied by Blue Gene machines in New York (one achieving 2097 MFLOPS/W) with the DEGIMA cluster in Nagasaki placing third with 1375 MFLOPS/W.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Because copper wires can transfer energy into a supercomputer with much higher power densities than forced air or circulating refrigerants can remove waste heat, the ability of the cooling systems to remove waste heat is a limiting factor.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] As of 2015, many existing supercomputers have more infrastructure capacity than the actual peak demand of the machine – designers generally conservatively design the power and cooling infrastructure to handle more than the theoretical peak electrical power consumed by the supercomputer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Since the end of the 20th century, supercomputer operating systems have undergone major transformations, based on the changes in supercomputer architecture.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] While early operating systems were custom tailored to each supercomputer to gain speed, the trend has been to move away from in-house operating systems to the adaptation of generic software such as Linux.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The parallel architectures of supercomputers often dictate the use of special programming techniques to exploit their speed.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Software tools for distributed processing include standard APIs such as MPI and PVM, VTL, and open source software such as Beowulf.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the most common scenario, environments such as PVM and MPI for loosely connected clusters and OpenMP for tightly coordinated shared memory machines are used.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Significant effort is required to optimize an algorithm for the interconnect characteristics of the machine it will be run on; the aim is to prevent any of the CPUs from wasting time waiting on data from other nodes.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] GPGPUs have hundreds of processor cores and are programmed using programming models such as CUDA or OpenCL.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Moreover, it is quite difficult to debug and test parallel programs.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Special techniques need to be used for testing and debugging such applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Opportunistic supercomputing is a form of networked grid computing whereby a "super virtual computer" of many loosely coupled volunteer computing machines performs very large computing tasks.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Grid computing has been applied to a number of large-scale embarrassingly parallel problems that require supercomputing performance scales.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] However, basic grid and cloud computing approaches that rely on volunteer computing cannot handle traditional supercomputing tasks such as fluid dynamic simulations.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The fastest grid computing system is the volunteer computing project Folding@home (F@h).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] As of April 2020, F@h reported 2.5 exaFLOPS of x86 processing power.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Of this, over 100 PFLOPS are contributed by clients running on various GPUs, and the rest from various CPU systems.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC) platform hosts a number of volunteer computing projects.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] As of February 2017, BOINC recorded a processing power of over 166 petaFLOPS through over 762 thousand active Computers (Hosts) on the network.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] As of October 2016, Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search's (GIMPS) distributed Mersenne Prime search achieved about 0.313 PFLOPS through over 1.3 million computers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The PrimeNet server has supported GIMPS's grid computing approach, one of the earliest volunteer computing projects, since 1997.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Quasi-opportunistic supercomputing is a form of distributed computing whereby the "super virtual computer" of many networked geographically disperse computers performs computing tasks that demand huge processing power.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Cloud computing with its recent and rapid expansions and development have grabbed the attention of high-performance computing (HPC) users and developers in recent years.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Cloud computing attempts to provide HPC-as-a-service exactly like other forms of services available in the cloud such as software as a service, platform as a service, and infrastructure as a service.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] HPC users may benefit from the cloud in different angles such as scalability, resources being on-demand, fast, and inexpensive.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] On the other hand, moving HPC applications have a set of challenges too.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Good examples of such challenges are virtualization overhead in the cloud, multi-tenancy of resources, and network latency issues.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Much research is currently being done to overcome these challenges and make HPC in the cloud a more realistic possibility.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In 2016, Penguin Computing, Parallel Works, R-HPC, Amazon Web Services, Univa, Silicon Graphics International, Rescale, Sabalcore, and Gomput started to offer HPC cloud computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The Penguin On Demand (POD) cloud is a bare-metal compute model to execute code, but each user is given virtualized login node.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] POD computing nodes are connected via non-virtualized 10 Gbit/s Ethernet or QDR InfiniBand networks.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] User connectivity to the POD data center ranges from 50 Mbit/s to 1 Gbit/s.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Citing Amazon's EC2 Elastic Compute Cloud, Penguin Computing argues that virtualization of compute nodes is not suitable for HPC.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Penguin Computing has also criticized that HPC clouds may have allocated computing nodes to customers that are far apart, causing latency that impairs performance for some HPC applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Supercomputers generally aim for the maximum in capability computing rather than capacity computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Capability computing is typically thought of as using the maximum computing power to solve a single large problem in the shortest amount of time.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Often a capability system is able to solve a problem of a size or complexity that no other computer can, e.g. a very complex weather simulation application.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Capacity computing, in contrast, is typically thought of as using efficient cost-effective computing power to solve a few somewhat large problems or many small problems.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Architectures that lend themselves to supporting many users for routine everyday tasks may have a lot of capacity but are not typically considered supercomputers, given that they do not solve a single very complex problem.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In general, the speed of supercomputers is measured and benchmarked in FLOPS (floating-point operations per second), and not in terms of MIPS (million instructions per second), as is the case with general-purpose computers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Exascale is computing performance in the exaFLOPS (EFLOPS) range.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] An EFLOPS is one quintillion (1018) FLOPS (one million TFLOPS).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] However, the performance of a supercomputer can be severely impacted by fluctuation brought on by elements like system load, network traffic, and concurrent processes, as mentioned by Brehm and Bruhwiler (2015).
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] No single number can reflect the overall performance of a computer system, yet the goal of the Linpack benchmark is to approximate how fast the computer solves numerical problems and it is widely used in the industry.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The LINPACK benchmark typically performs LU decomposition of a large matrix.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Since 1993, the fastest supercomputers have been ranked on the TOP500 list according to their LINPACK benchmark results.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The list does not claim to be unbiased or definitive, but it is a widely cited current definition of the "fastest" supercomputer available at any given time.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] This is a list of the computers which appeared at the top of the TOP500 list since June 1993, and the "Peak speed" is given as the "Rmax" rating.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In 2018, Lenovo became the world's largest provider for the TOP500 supercomputers with 117 units produced.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The application of supercomputers has evolved significantly since the 1970s, expanding across numerous fields of scientific and governmental research.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the 1970s, the Cray-1 supercomputer was instrumental in early weather forecasting and aerodynamic research.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The scope broadened in the 1980s with machines like the CDC Cyber facilitating probabilistic analyses and modeling radiation shielding.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The 1990s saw supercomputers, such as the EFF DES cracker, applied to brute-force tasks like code-breaking.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Moving into the 2000s, supercomputers became crucial for national security applications; the ASCI Q was used to conduct 3D nuclear test simulations, satisfying the requirements of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty without physical testing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The 2010s brought advancements in molecular dynamics simulations, exemplified by the use of the Tianhe-1A.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The trend has continued into the 2020s, with supercomputers providing powerful tools for research into outbreak prevention and electrochemical reactions.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Beyond these specific decades, supercomputers have been pivotal in major scientific endeavors.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] For instance, the IBM Blue Gene/P was used to simulate a network of artificial neurons equivalent to one percent of a human cerebral cortex (1.6 billion neurons and 9 trillion connections), and the same team later simulated the entirety of a rat's brain.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Modern applications are diverse and critical.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Weather forecasting relies heavily on supercomputing power, with the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration utilizing these systems to process vast quantities of observational data to enhance forecast accuracy.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The United States also employs supercomputers through the Advanced Simulation and Computing Program to maintain and simulate its nuclear stockpile.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The field has its challenges, as highlighted by IBM's abandonment of the ambitious Blue Waters petascale project in 2011.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Despite such setbacks, the utility of supercomputers continues to grow.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] A recent example of their critical role occurred in early 2020, when supercomputers were rapidly deployed to run extensive simulations using numerous paralleled CPUs to identify compounds with the potential to stop the spread of COVID-19.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the 2010s, China, the United States, the European Union, and others competed to be the first to create a 1 exaFLOP (1018 or one quintillion FLOPS) supercomputer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] DeBenedictis of Sandia National Laboratories has theorized that a zettaFLOPS (1021 or one sextillion FLOPS) computer is required to accomplish full weather modeling, which could cover a two-week time span accurately.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Such systems might be built around 2030.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Many Monte Carlo simulations use the same algorithm to process a randomly generated data set; particularly, integro-differential equations describing physical transport processes, the random paths, collisions, and energy and momentum depositions of neutrons, photons, ions, electrons, etc.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The next step for microprocessors may be into the third dimension; and specializing to Monte Carlo, the many layers could be identical, simplifying the design and manufacture process.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The cost of operating high performance supercomputers has risen, mainly due to increasing power consumption.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the mid-1990s a top 10 supercomputer required in the range of 100 kilowatts, in 2010 the top 10 supercomputers required between 1 and 2 megawatts.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] A 2010 study commissioned by DARPA identified power consumption as the most pervasive challenge in achieving Exascale computing.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] At the time a megawatt per year in energy consumption cost about 1 million dollars.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Supercomputing facilities were constructed to efficiently remove the increasing amount of heat produced by modern multi-core central processing units.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Based on the energy consumption of the Green 500 list of supercomputers between 2007 and 2011, a supercomputer with 1 exaFLOPS in 2011 would have required nearly 500 megawatts.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Operating systems were developed for existing hardware to conserve energy whenever possible.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] CPU cores not in use during the execution of a parallelized application were put into low-power states, producing energy savings for some supercomputing applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The increasing cost of operating supercomputers has been a driving factor in a trend toward bundling of resources through a distributed supercomputer infrastructure.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] National supercomputing centers first emerged in the US, followed by Germany and Japan.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The European Union launched the Partnership for Advanced Computing in Europe (PRACE) with the aim of creating a persistent pan-European supercomputer infrastructure with services to support scientists across the European Union in porting, scaling and optimizing supercomputing applications.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Iceland built the world's first zero-emission supercomputer.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Located at the Thor Data Center in Reykjavík, Iceland, this supercomputer relies on completely renewable sources for its power rather than fossil fuels.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] The colder climate also reduces the need for active cooling, making it one of the greenest facilities in the world of computers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Funding supercomputer hardware also became increasingly difficult.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the mid-1990s a top 10 supercomputer cost about 10 million euros, while in 2010 the top 10 supercomputers required an investment of between 40 and 50 million euros.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the 2000s national governments put in place different strategies to fund supercomputers.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] In the UK the national government funded supercomputers entirely and high performance computing was put under the control of a national funding agency.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Germany developed a mixed funding model, pooling local state funding and federal funding.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] Examples of supercomputers in fiction include HAL 9000, Multivac, The Machine Stops, GLaDOS, SHODAN, The Evitable Conflict, Vulcan's Hammer, Colossus, WOPR, AM, and Deep Thought.
[src:mpi-parallel-computing/supercomputer] A supercomputer from Thinking Machines was mentioned as the supercomputer used to sequence the DNA extracted from preserved parasites in the Jurassic Park series.
